        "timestamp": "2021-10-14 18:38:01.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\n(1 comment)\n\n> Patch Set 2:\n> \n> As for the other patchset, I don't see the point to split tox lists in multiple runs.\n> For a very small gain in duration (not so sure), you would have quickly to manage excludes per branch.\n> \n> Tox could be the only entry point and then you would only define default env lists per branches.\n> Here it asks for backports or to add exclude per stream.\n> \n> Here is an example excluding streams:\n> https://git.opnfv.org/releng/tree/jjb/functest/xtesting.yaml#n217\n\n> Patch Set 2:\n> \n> Sorry, just noticed Cedric's comment. Can you guys please respond to it?\n\nThanks Cédric for the example. I've tried to adapt here to the situation here.\nLet me know if it is OK\n\n@Jessica I'll let OOM committers answer about the other proposal because I don't know the reason behind the actual policy.\nI agree with Cédric that managing directly env in OOM repo tox.ini files per branch would be much easier. The actual OOM policy is not to backport tox new linters to old branches as explained in\nhttps://gerrit.onap.org/r/c/oom/+/120407\nAs the result, we have to configure every exclude combinatory, what can quickly become really cumbersome.",
        "patchset_number": 3
